So regal! Morley George understood the assignment, channeling his inner George Costanza during our recent family photos🎄♥️

A few new decor additions and some enhancement to existing ones has given our veranda a nice spruce up for the holidays! 🎄

Thanks to, @kentbuildingsupplies I was able to gather everything I needed to complete this look:
• Fresh greenery - Kent has a great selection of cut stems and foliage. I used cedar for the arrangement beside the door.
• Garland - I thought I was going to bees to replace our banister garland, however by adding another string of garland and some new accents, it looks brand new! Definitely an easy way to keep cost and waste down. I also left one bundle of garland folded and put it in the crate on the veranda dresser. I added some faux holly and pine cones for an easy decor fill.
• Lights - We added a mix of small and bigger bulbs, all in warm white, to all of the garland for a larger impact and the two sizes have created a nice effect.

The old door, Christmas tree was purchased by a local woodworker and I love it so much! 

Thanks to, @kentbuildingsupplies for partnering with us to update our outdoor decor this year!

Dare I commit to this being a New Years tradition? I’ve always wanted to do a polar dip and with today’s balmy weather, it seemed like a sign not to wait any longer. One of the easiest DIYs I’ve done in a long time and equally one of the most impressive (if I do say so myself)!

I’ve wanted to do a refresh in our downstairs bathroom for ages. The existing neutral palette was calling for some colour and character. Using, @beyondpaintdiy in the colour Nantucket the vanity no longer looks generic and is a great jumping off point for the rest of the updates I’m planning! Stay tuned for those 😊 In the meantime, if you’re thinking about painting your vanity, or going all out on a big project like your kitchen cupboards, I simply cannot recommend Beyond Paint enough. It’s so incredibly easy to use, affordable & durable! I love chatting about painting projects and am always happy to answer any questions I can, so feel free to DM.

Materials:
- @beyondpaintdiy in Nantucket
- Small fluffy roller
- Paint brush
- Painters tape (I like to wing it and go without, but best to use if you’re not sure)

Steps:
- Prep surface (I use TSP and wipe down all areas to be painted)
- Stipple the paint in all the areas that the roller will not be able to reach
- Roll all areas
- Two coats in total

Big thank you to @kentbuildingsupplies for partnering with us on this fun #kentchallenge - we look forward to the next one!

#kentbuildingsupplies #kentpartner #beyondpaint #vanitymakeover

I created this little reel last week… and then got distracted and didn’t share. Anyway. This video is a quick sum up of all the little things I’ve been enjoying lately. What I didn’t initially realize is that it also plays out like a perfect winter morning.

@crate61organics Lavender - beautiful, Canadian, organic soaps. I haven’t tried all their scents because I keep coming back to the lavender. It’s just so lovely.
Tulips - bought as a little treat for the house. Against the backdrop of the snow, out the window, they’re such an uplifting sight on the table.
@garneauslippers Sheepskin Slipper Booties. Cozy, warm and comfortable my newest Garneau slippers are the actual best.
The Spoon Stealer novel - anything to do with Cape Breton has my heart and this book is all things sweet about the island. I’ve been reading slowly and savouring it.
Oatmeal - pretty basic but a winter comfort. Stove made oatmeal, milk around the outer edge, maple syrup or runny honey and berries.
Tazo Chai Tea Latte - half a mug of Tazo heated in the microwave, half milk warmed and frothed in my frother and then a sprinkle of cinnamon to be fancy.
Birdtalker - I just love this album and find myself listening to it a lot lately.

What are some of your current favourites? I’d love to hear ♥️
An after school date with my best girl. The sea, sun and some silliness. It doesn’t get much better ♥️

A quick photo recap of our Easter Weekend. It was a very quiet long weekend. This veer from the usual festivities suited us just fine. In fact, I said to Rob this morning how refreshing it is to sometimes not have any holiday plans. Apart from the traditional egg hunt on Sunday morning, everything that made up this year’s Easter celebration was almost the opposite of what we normally do; right down to our Easter dinner of tacos. We managed to fit in some games, a really nice post-Fiona return to Roy’s Island and constant hoop action of driveway basketball. However you celebrated, I hope you had a wonderful Easter ♥️

After twenty plus years, I’ve (finally) come back to reading. As a child, I couldn’t seem to get my hands on enough books, but then somehow in my twenties it got away from me… 

I started 2023, by wanting to commit to reading 20 books over 12 months and so far, I’ve managed to finish 33 in a little over four. I squeeze in pages and chapters between all my daily obligations and have been surprised by just how much I’ve been able to read. Then again, we make take for the things that matter and bring us joy. 

Anyway, the sum of my rambling is simply that I’m so grateful to back enjoying something that I love. Tell me, what are you reading? Do you have any book recommendations?!

Where to even begin with captioning this update to our kitchen. There’s just SO much to share! The most obvious is that we’re beyond pleased with the outcome. The refresh of a new countertop and backsplash install has completed the transformation of our kitchen from dark and drab to light and lovely! It doesn’t even look like the same space😊

However, if you haven’t been following along with this project; let me quickly catch you up… Our kitchen was dated. Think creams, warm orangey wood tones, browns, and black. Needless to say we were overdue for a change. The vision was simple: light, fresh, and clean.

Phase One (see other reel for before/after): 
• Paint existing cabinetry using @beyondpaintdiy ✔️
• Update hardware to matte black ✔️

This was an amazing change on its own, but we weren’t done!

Phase two (recent update):
• Install new countertop. We selected a countertop to compliment both the warm tones that still exist in the rest of the house and the fresh white of the updates. The countertop is from @kentbuildingsupplies and is Arborite P394 VL Arctic Snow. As an additional note, Kent could not have made this part of the project any easier. Once the countertop was ordered, a sales associate organized an installer to remove the existing top and install the new. They even took away the older countertop!
•Backsplash: The credit for this part of the makeover goes entirely to Rob. He had no prior experience installing tile or a backsplash of any kind, but he nailed it. Not to take too much credit away from his efforts, but we used @speedtiles which kept things simple! Product specifics: Stone SpeedTiles in the Pinot profile/colour. This is a new option from the brand as a groutable Peel & Stick with real stone. It’s 2x faster to install than regular mosaic and doesn’t require mortar(🙌🏻). This product allows for endless DIY possibilities, even in a bath setting (ensure you research prior to install). Can be placed on any clean, smooth, leveled and non-porous surface e.g. primed drywall.

All products for the entire project can be found at @kentbuildingsupplies and of course, I’m always keen to chat project details! #kentpartner

Summer traditions. 

For me the end of July, or the midpoint of the summer season, is synonymous with picking endless amounts of high bush blueberries. Oma Kate, or Rob’s Mum as she’s also known, has the best bushes and is happiest when her family enjoys the harvest 🫐

The first few years of picking, I did so with babies on blankets. They snacked on the haul while I gathered bowlfuls. Then that shifted quickly to helping sticky toddler hands learn how to ‘gently’ pick the berries. And now I find myself working alongside my children who are seasoned pros. Ah, how quickly it all changes!

I believe at one point I filmed a little vlog about this. I should perhaps give it a watch.

These little traditions, the things we do that evolve yet somehow always bring the same comfort and joy, are my favourite.

What are your summer traditions?

#novascotia #blueberriesfordays

I’ve loved old things my whole life. For as long as I can remember I’ve always had a collection of small relics. Things that held little value to anyone else, but I treasured them. Lately, I’ve been on a bit of a roll finding so many gems! Now to find a special place for each of them… 

Little tip, if you’re buying from an antique store or similar, ask if the seller knows the story behind the pieces you’re buying. The chalkboard in this video came from an old school close to where I live now. It’s no longer there, but I have fond memories of it from when I was younger. The carved bird? The creative work of a folk artist who made a lot of them (80+), all different in their own way. His vision was to have them all sit on different branches of a carved tree. However sadly, he passed away before he was able to complete his project. Now that I know this backstory, I like to think the gentlemen would be pleased knowing that his pieces are being enjoyed in so many homes. Some even across the country.

Anyway. Old things. I love them.

We recently visited the Highland Village Museum in Iona, Cape Breton. It is such a lovely spot! The whole experience was completely immersive. Each of us learned so much about the settlers who made the trip across the sea to call the Maritimes home. It was refreshing, even for a short time, to escape back to a period of simplicity and to be reminded of the beauty of the Gaelic culture.

If you’re in the area, I would 10/10 recommend taking in this gem. Give yourself an hour or so to explore and be sure to engage with the villagers because they know so much!

@visitcapebretonisland
#capebreton

👩🏻‍🎨🎃 Not ready to start carving? Or want to skip the mess, but not the fun? Paint your pumpkins! This was a super easy and actually relaxing lil project. 
It’s pretty straight forward but a couple of tips:
• Have your pumpkins be at room temperature. I brought mine in overnight. No condensation will allow the paint to stick better.
• Use good paint! I used my favourite, @beyondpaintdiy from @kentbuildingsupplies One coat was all that was necessary because the quality is fantastic. I love this paint… not that you’re unaware ☺️

I’ve saved some pumpkins for the kids to paint and of course we’ll still carve, but (per tradition) that won’t happen until closer to the 31st. 

These pumpkins have added such a fun touch of decor to our front step. Thanks to @kentbuildingsupplies for teaming with us on this! 🎃

#kentbuildingsupplies #kentpartner #halloweendiy #paintedpumpkins
Enjoying the last of the leaf piles 🍂🍁

Curacao. On our recent vacation, we got to spend an amazing day touring this quaint little Dutch Caribbean island. While we certainly didn’t get to see everything, we did manage to enjoy some new experiences!
• ‘The Blue Room’ - A cave, that once inside is filled with such a gorgeous blue light. It’s only accessible by swimming underneath the cave wall; which isn’t a task for a nervous or inexperienced swimmer. This means unfortunately our children weren’t able to join us. They’re strong swimmers, but not being able to come up for air during the passing was far too risky at their ages. They did however get to participate in the hike to the shoreline and plunge into the brilliant blue water.
• Swimming with sea turtles - This was one the kids could easily do and they loved every minute of it. We accessed a public beach known for this attraction and swam around with the friendly creatures for nearly an hour. They weren’t shy and came right up to us! We also used snorkels to get a closeup look at the turtles and beautiful fish. They’re a must if you want the full experience!
• Queen Emma Bridge - This pedestrian bridge is in the heart of the capital city, Willemstad, and is so neat! We walked it and then from a nearby brasserie, enjoyed watching the bridge swing open to allow boats through. It happens so quickly and is definitely impressive.
• Shopping - We did a little browsing around Willemstad and loved the Dutch feel. It reminded us a bit of being back in Holland especially the Gouda stands!

There’s a lot of perks to cruising (more on that soon), but one for certain is the ability to take in smaller places that you may otherwise not make a dedicated trip to see.

#curacao #willemstad

Keeping with tradition, I’m going to be taking a break from socials until the new year. I’m looking forward to playing loads of board games, enjoying lots of seaside walks, cozy reading, movie watching and plenty of sweet treats. Most of all, time spent with my family and dear friends ♥️

This year, while not without its challenges, has been good to me. Lots of lessons and opportunity for growth. Looking ahead, on many fronts, 2024 is a big one. Much to anticipate!

However, I don’t want to rush this magical season. So before I sign off…

From me to you, my family to yours, I wish you the warmest holiday ever. If this time of year is a challenging one, know I’m thinking of you. Thank you for spending another year following this creative outlet of mine, it means a lot. Merry Christmas and truly all the very best in 2024 ♥️

Janine & Co. xx

Cue the sentimental music and the highlight reel of my past 365 days. It was a good one. More days spent smiling than not, lots of laughs, goals accomplished, and lessons learned.

Looking forward, I’ve never felt more settled or excited going into a new year than I am starting 2024 and that’s a great way to begin.

I hope this year surprises you in big ways and small ones, too. Cheers to the next 365…

Life update ♥️ I have accepted a full-time, permanent job with a local company as their Social Media and Marketing Specialist. This new chapter is such an exciting one. The job itself checks all the boxes (amazing team, creative work, travel, and it really goes on and on). Stepping away from freelance employment has also arrived during a very welcomed season in my life. All of this has provided great pause for reflection and immense gratitude toward a beautiful, full-circle pursuit.

I chose this particular photo because it was taken for my social media accounts right when things began to pick-up and my hobby turned into employment. What a wonderful time that was. I feel the same stirring excitement now.

When I started sharing my life on social media, I did it because I craved connection and equally a creative outlet. I got to share some of my journey in the early years of motherhood and now have such a unique keepsake to treasure of those fleeting years that separate the then and now. I’ve worked with brands I love, enjoyed opportunities I would never otherwise have had, but most of all I’m genuinely grateful for the connections and friendships I’ve been blessed to make over the last (almost) nine years!

Admittedly, I don’t know where this leaves this account. I certainly have a pull to continue to share, but less so of my family and with no posting predictability (was there ever? ha). It also feels appropriate to make my YouTube channel private. After years of saying I planned on coming back to video, it’s very clear, and especially now, that it isn’t happening!

Anyway. Lots to look forward to and equally be thankful for. If the last nine years has taught me anything, it’s to take the risk. Do the thing. Chase the dream. Nothing is placed on your path without reason.

Cheers to the second act!
